node.text: For 50 years, the Congressional Black Caucus has fought to ensure that every American has equal opportunity—and a voice in our democracy. Congratulations on this milestone. You truly are the conscience of Congress.

node.text:
Childcare remains too expensive and out of reach for far too many working families in our country. Today, I joined Secretary Yellen at the @treasurydept to discuss how our Administration’s Build Back Better Agenda will make historic investments in childcare—and make childcare affordable for every family.
 
I believe, this is about our responsibility, as a government, to ensure everyone—women and men alike—have the power to determine their own future.  It’s about giving people options to live a life of dignity.  And that includes affordable and accessible options to send their children to high-quality childcare.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Vice President Kamala Harris on September 14, 2021. May be a black-and-white image of 1 person.

node.text:
I want to tell you about a personal hero of mine—Constance Baker Motley. Today, on what would have been her 100th birthday, we celebrate her extraordinary legacy. 
 
Constance Baker Motley decided to go to law school even after being told that “women don’t get anywhere in the law.” She helped write the brief for Brown v. Board of Education and argued 10 cases before the United States Supreme Court, winning 9 of them. She was the first Black woman appointed to a federal court judgeship—and the only one for more than a decade.
 
Constance Baker Motley showed us the power of the law to affect change, and she taught us to see what can be, unburdened by what has been. We must call on her wisdom as we carry on the work—and in particular, the work to protect the fundamental right to vote. This year alone, 18 states have passed 30 anti-voter laws. These laws disproportionately impact communities of color—and are designed to make it harder for people to vote.
 
President Joe Biden and I are fighting back. We are working to pass the Freedom to Vote Act and the John Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act. Together, I believe we can get this done. So, let us commit ourselves to the values Constance Baker Motley held dear. Equality. Justice. And the right of all people to participate fully in our society—and to determine their own futures.

node.text: The right of women to make decisions about their own bodies is non-negotiable—and the law in Texas is unconscionable. Last week, I met with patients and providers to hear about the impact of Texas Senate Bill 8. Our Administration will fight that law—and others like it.

node.text: To the family members, friends and all those who lost someone they love on September 11th or in its aftermath, please know that we see you—and that our nation stands with you.

node.text: On this 20th anniversary of September 11, 2001, we must challenge ourselves to look back—for the sake of our children and their children. For that same reason, we must also look forward. We must also look toward the future. Because in the end, that is what the 40 passengers and crew members of Flight 93 were fighting for: Their future, and ours.

node.text:
From Day One, President Biden and I have been committed to fighting for Historically Black Colleges and Universities. Our Administration provided billions in relief to HBCUs through the American Rescue Plan. And our Build Back Better Agenda goes even further. We plan to make college more affordable, including at HBCUs. We also plan to put billions of dollars toward HBCU research facilities and developing the next generation of leaders in STEM.

Thank you, Hampton University for welcoming me to your home by the sea today. This HBCU grad was happy to celebrate #HBCUWeek with you!

Hampton—like HBCUs everywhere—are not just competing, they are leading on STEM education. Our Build Back Better Agenda would make an historic investment in R&D infrastructure for HBCUs. Today I met with students at Hampton to hear their vision for the future. 
 
Investments in STEM programs on campuses like @_hamptonu are critical to keeping our nation competitive in this new era. I toured Hampton’s Center for Atmospheric Sciences to see the impressive work students are doing to study our climate.

node.text:
Every year, students and alumni across America from Historically Black Colleges and Universities come together to celebrate the rich history and important contributions of these esteemed institutions.

I am a proud graduate of an HBCU. My time at @howard1867 shaped me into the person I am today. At Howard, I was on the debate team and pledged to @akaalphachapter. I also ran for my very first elected office as the freshman class representative of the Liberal Arts Student Council.

Today, the extraordinary students at our nation's HBCUs are focused and driven. They are at the forefront of scientific research, interning on Capitol Hill, starting their own businesses, and transforming our country through poetry, music, and dance. HBCU students know there are no false choices. You can do anything.

HBCU students—@POTUS and I are counting on you and investing in you. Our world faces many challenges and we need our brightest minds to take them on. The most important lesson I learned while I attended an HBCU: You do not only have the capacity to be great. You have the responsibility to live up to that potential. So speak your truth. Lead with purpose. And remember that wherever you go, you are never alone, because your HBCU family is always with you. Happy #HBCUWeek!
